<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOVIES TO TAPE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Que Viva Mexico! (Bravo Monday at 11 p.m.): This is a fascinating assemblage of 
Sergei Eisenstein's aborted 1932 poetic epic of Mexican peasantry. (1:30) 
</P>
<P>
The Best Years of Our Lives (TNT Thursday at 5 p.m.): The key to this enduring 
William Wyler-Samuel Goldwyn postwar classic is that it touches upon timeless 
themes of homecoming and family relationships and that its three very different 
returning soldiers -- Fredric March, Harold Russell and Dana Andrews -- allow 
for wide identification. (3:45) 
</P>
<P>
Danton (A&amp;E early Sunday at 1 a.m.): Bleakly beautiful and richly detailed, 
Andrzej Wajda's 1982 film is an electrifying depiction of a society hurtling 
toward chaos. Gerard Depardieu is superb in the title role as the boisterous 
and earthy revolutionary. (3:00) 
</P>
</TEXT>
