<HEADLINE>
<P>
LEGALIZING STREET VENDORS: MOVE TO AVOID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Iwould like to comment on "Vendors vs. the Law" (June 27). 
</P>
<P>
I was born and raised in Venezuela where street vendors, although illegal, are 
as thick as flies and just as annoying. 
</P>
<P>
In business districts, they take up most of the sidewalk, creating hazards for 
the pedestrians and large amounts of trash that wind up on the street. The 
vendors are unfair competition for merchants since they do not have to pay rent 
or taxes and have no upkeep. Peeled fruit and most foods tend to develop nasty 
bacteria that can make unsuspecting customers extremely ill. 
</P>
<P>
If vending were legalized as LAPD Chief Daryl Gates longs for, we would have 
uncontrolled vendors all over the city and another incompetent government 
agency that will be overworked and understaffed. Councilman Michael Woo should 
take a little trip down to Latin America and experience vendors personally 
before creating another government monster. Believe me, they are not something 
we would like to add to our way of life in this city. 
</P>
<P>
MERCEDES WEIL 
</P>
<P>
Canoga Park 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
