<HEADLINE>
<P>
DORM DILEMMA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
John Berol ("A Solution to Mini-Dorm Dilemma," June 24) makes an eloquent 
appeal for protecting our neighborhoods from the insidious erosion inflicted by 
unregulated housing. 
</P>
<P>
The economic appeal provided by renting single-family houses to students is 
hard to resist. 
</P>
<P>
Pacific Beach, like La Jolla and the college area, is particularly hard-hit by 
the additional traffic, noise and all-around density fostered by this practice. 
</P>
<P>
The result: as houses fill to capacity and streets become long parking lots, 
any semblance of a single-family neighborhood is lost to the expediency of 
housing more and more people. As long as the colleges and universities ignore 
their responsibility to house the students they attract to our city, the city 
at large will suffer, students and residents alike. 
</P>
<P>
ALFRED C. STROHLEIN 
</P>
<P>
San Diego 
</P>
</TEXT>
