<HEADLINE>
<P>
GOLF ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
WADKINS INCREASES LEAD TO 3 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Twenty years after losing to Lanny Wadkins as an amateur, Curtis Strange gets a 
shot at revenge today in Williamsburg, Va. And this time there's $180,000 on 
the line. And it's on Strange's home course. 
</P>
<P>
"He's a good front-runner, he's a tough competitor and he's got a lot of guts," 
Strange said. "But I've got my share, too. It ought to be fun." 
</P>
<P>
Strange has ground to make up. On Saturday, Wadkins used three birdie surges to 
shoot a four-under-par 67 that gave him a three-stroke lead over Strange going 
into the final round of the Anheuser-Busch Golf Classic. 
</P>
<P>
Wadkins, a native of nearby Richmond, made consecutive birdies at three 
different stages of his round at the Kingsmill Golf Club. He also had two 
bogeys which left him at 15-under-par 198 for the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
Strange, who was born in nearby Norfolk, chipped in from the fringe on the 
par-four 18th for a birdie. His 68 put him at 12-under 201. 
</P>
<P>
Because Wadkins is 40 and Strange is 35, they didn't meet often as amateurs. 
But Strange recalled that Wadkins did beat him in the semifinals of the 1970 
Virginia Amateur. 
</P>
<P>
"I was always kind of right behind Lanny," Strange said. "Lanny and I have 
become friends -- very good friends." 
</P>
<P>
In addition to sharing a home state, Strange followed Wadkins in college golf 
at Wake Forest. But Wadkins tried to downplay the parallels between himself and 
Strange, whose 17 victories include two U.S. Opens. 
</P>
<P>
"He's a tough competitor. He's capable of playing better than anyone," said 
Wadkins, who is seeking his 19th career title. 
</P>
<P>
Betsy King is leading the Jamie Farr Toledo Classic, although you'd never know 
it to listen to her talk. 
</P>
<P>
"I should have quit after the front nine," she said after shooting a 
one-under-par 70 for a one-stroke lead over Chris Johnson and Tina Purtzer 
heading into today's final round. 
</P>
<P>
King is at four-under-par 138 through 36 holes. She built a two-stroke lead 
with three consecutive birdies, then came back after dropping three shots to 
par by making a 15-foot birdie putt on the 18th hole. 
</P>
<P>
George Archer ignored back problems while shooting a five-under-par 67, 
building a two-shot lead over Frank Beard, Homero Blancas and Charles Coody 
after two rounds of the senior tour Northville Long Island Classic at Jericho, 
N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
Archer, who began the day two strokes behind first-round leader Gary Player, 
used an eagle on the par-five 10th hole and a birdie on No. 11 to build a 
four-stroke margin. But bogeys on Nos. 13 and 16 pulled him back to the field 
at 136, eight shots under par. 
</P>
</TEXT>
