<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: THE 1990 DOONESBURY STAMP ALBUM BY GARRY TRUDEAU (PENGUIN: 
$8.95) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Unlike most contemporary cartoonists, Garry Trudeau has stubbornly resisted 
attempts to merchandise his strip. The first "Doonesbury" license product was 
created to raise money for "Writers' Voices," a national program that provides 
accessible reading material to the 27 million American adults who are 
illiterate or have only limited reading skills. 
</P>
<P>
This spoof of a conventional stamp album allows Trudeau an opportunity to show 
off his skill as a graphic artist. The cleverly designed pseudo-stamps include 
images of his familiar characters (Zonker darkens like a roasting Thanksgiving 
turkey as his tan deepens from "Gaucho Glow" to "Malibu Melt") and a series of 
mordant lampoons of George Bush. A map showing the homes of the regular 
"Doonesbury" cast includes special graphic symbols indicating Elvis sightings, 
oil spills, Geraldo-free zones and Towns Without Pity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
