<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Racing in rainy conditions, Wayne Rainey of Downey led throughout to win the 
Belgian 500cc motorcycling Grand Prix, extending his world championship lead 
over Kevin Schwantz of Paige, Tex., at Spa-Francorchamps, Belgium. 
</P>
<P>
France's Jean-Philippe Ruggia, who had never competed in a 500cc event on a wet 
track, finished second. 
</P>
<P>
Rainey's victory was his fifth in nine races this year and left him with 168 
points in the world championship series, 35 ahead of Schwantz with six races 
remaining. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Game Story 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA070890-0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 244552 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 8, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 16; Column 5; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
80 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Harvard University reached two finals at the Henley Royal Regatta, at 
Henley-On-Thames, England. 
</P>
<P>
The senior heavyweight crew reached the final of the Ladies Plate, the 
second-most important event for eights, for the second successive year, 
defeating the University of Wisconsin by two boat lengths in rough water. 
</P>
<P>
Harvard will face London University in the final today. 
</P>
<P>
The Crimson also reached the final of the Thames Cup, the third-most 
prestigious race for eights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
